{"title_page": "Astilbe", "text_new": "{{automatic taxobox\n|image = Astilbe arendsii1.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Astilbe arendsii'' in flower\n|taxon = Astilbe\n|authority = [[Francis Buchanan-Hamilton|Buch.-Ham.]] ex [[David Don|D.Don]]\n|subdivision_ranks = Species\n|subdivision = See text\n|type_species = ''[[Astilbe rivularis]]'' <small>[[Buch.-Ham.]] ex [[D.Don]]</small> \n}}\n\n'''''Astilbe''''' {{IPAc-en|\u0259|\u02c8|s|t|\u026a|l|b|i\u02d0}}<ref>''Sunset Western Garden Book,'' 1995:606\u2013607</ref> is a [[genus]] of 18 [[species]] of [[rhizome|rhizomatous]] [[flowering plant]]s within the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Saxifragaceae]], [[native plant|native]] to mountain ravines and woodlands in Asia and North America.<ref>{{cite book|title=RHS A-Z encyclopedia of garden plants|year=2008|publisher=Dorling Kindersley|location=United Kingdom|isbn=1405332964|pages=1136}}</ref> Some species are known by the common names '''false goat's beard''' and '''false spirea'''.\n\nThese [[hardiness (plants)|hardy]] [[herbaceous]] [[perennial plant|perennials]] are cultivated by gardeners for their large, handsome, often fern-like foliage and dense, feathery plumes of flowers. They are widely adapted to shade and water-logged conditions, hence they are particularly associated with pond-side planting. They also tolerate clay soils well. Numerous [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrid]] [[cultivars]] have been raised. Flowers of at least some ''Astilbe'' species have a strong and pleasant aroma. Some species, including ''[[Astilbe rivularis]]'', are used in traditional medicine.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=O'Neill |first1=Alexander |display-authors=etal |author2= |date=2017-03-29 |title=Integrating ethnobiological knowledge into biodiversity conservation in the Eastern Himalayas |url=https://ethnobiomed.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13002-017-0148-9 |journal=Journal of Ethnobiology and Ethnomedicine |volume=13 |issue=21 |pages= |doi=10.1186/s13002-017-0148-9 |access-date=2017-05-11 |pmc=5372287 |pmid=28356115}}</ref>\n\n==Species==\nSpecies of ''Astilbe'' include:\n*''[[Astilbe biternata]]'' (Vent.) Britt. \n*''[[Astilbe chinensis]]'' (Maxim.) Franch. & Sav.   \n*''[[Astilbe crispa]]'' (Arends) Bergmans \n*''[[Astilbe grandis]]'' Stapf ex E. H. Wilson \u2013 Korean false goat's beard<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.forest.go.kr/kna/special/download/English_Names_for_Korean_Native_Plants.pdf |title=English Names for Korean Native Plants |publisher=[[Korea National Arboretum]] |year=2015 |isbn=978-89-97450-98-5 |location=Pocheon |pages=367 |access-date=24 December 2016 |via=[[Korea Forest Service]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525105020/http://www.forest.go.kr/kna/special/download/English_Names_for_Korean_Native_Plants.pdf |archivedate=25 May 2017 }}</ref>\n*''[[Astilbe japonica]]'' ([[Charles Fran\u00e7ois Antoine Morren|C.Morren]] & Decne.) A.Gray\n*''[[Astilbe longicarpa]]'' (Hayata) Hayata\n*''[[Astilbe macroflora]]'' Hayata \n*''[[Astilbe microphylla]]'' Knoll\n**[[Astilbe microphylla var. riparia|''Astilbe microphylla'' var. ''riparia'']] [[List of botanists by author abbreviation#H|Hatus]]. \n*''[[Astilbe platyphylla]]'' H. Boiss. \n*''[[Astilbe rivularis]]'' Buch.-Ham. ex D. Don \n**[[Astilbe rivularis var. angustifoliolata|''Astilbe rivularis'' var. ''angustifoliolata'']] H. Hara\n**[[Astilbe rivularis var. myriantha|''Astilbe rivularis'' var. ''myriantha'']] (Diels) J. T. Pan \n*''[[Astilbe rubra]]'' Hook. f. & Thomson \u2013 false goat's beard<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''[[Astilbe sikokumontana]]'' Koidz.   \n*''[[Astilbe simplicifolia]]'' Makino \u2013 entire-leaf false goat's beard<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''[[Astilbe thunbergii]]'' (Siebold & Zucc.) Miq.   \n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. congesta|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''congesta'']] H. [[Henri de Boissieu|Boissieu]]\n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. fujisanensis|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''fujisanensis'']] (Nakai) Ohwi \n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. hachijoensis|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''hachijoensis'']] (Nakai) Ohwi \n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. kiusiana|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''kiusiana'']] Hara\n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. longipedicellata|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''longipedicellata'']] Hatus.\n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. okuyamae|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''okuyamae'']] (Hara) [[List of botanists by author abbreviation#O|Ohwi]] \n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. shikokiana|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''shikokiana'']] (Nakai) Ohwi \n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. terrestris|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''terrestris'']] (Nakai) Ohwi\n\n==Cultivar groups==\nCommonly accepted [[cultivar]] groups are:\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Astilbe Arendsii Group|''Astilbe'' Arendsii Group]]\n*''Astilbe'' Crispa Group\n*''Astilbe'' Japonica Group\n*''Astilbe'' Simplicifolia Group\n{{div col end}}\n\nThe following varieties and cultivars have gained the [[Royal Horticultural Society]]'s [[Award of Garden Merit]]:\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*'Brautschleier' (Arendsii Group) - white<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Brautschleier'|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/112600/Astilbe-Brautschleier-(%25C3%2597-arendsii)/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*'Bronce elegans' (Simplicifolia) - salmon pink<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Bronce Elegans'|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/90688/Astilbe-Bronce-Elegans-(simplicifolia-hybrid)/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*''A. chinensis'' var. ''pumila'' - mauve<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe chinensis'' var. ''pumila''|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/54603/Astilbe-chinensis-var-pumila/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*''A. chinensis'' var. ''taqueti'' 'Superba'<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/89593/Astilbe-chinensis-var-taquetii-Superba/Details | title = ''A. chinensis'' var. taqueti 'Superba' | publisher = RHS | accessdate = 12 April 2020}}</ref> - rose/mauve\n*'Fanal' (Arendsii) - crimson<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Fanal'|url=\nhttps://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/95205/Astilbe-Fanal-(%25C3%2597-arendsii)/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*''A. glaberrima'' var. ''saxatilis'' - pink & white, prostrate<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe glaberrima'' var. ''saxatilis''|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/95706/Astilbe-glaberrima-var-saxatilis/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*'Rheinland' (Japonica) - pale pink<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Rheinland'|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/97102/Astilbe-Rheinland-(japonica-hybrid)/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*''A. simplicifolia''<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe simplicifolia''|url=\nhttps://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/1841/Astilbe-simplicifolia/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*'Sprite' (Simplicifolia) - pale pink<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Sprite'|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/93253/Astilbe-Sprite-(simplicifolia-hybrid)/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*'Straussenfeder' (Thunbergii) - pink<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Straussenfeder'|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/94693/Astilbe-Straussenfeder-(thunbergii-hybrid)/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*''A.'' \u00d7 ''crispa'' 'Perkeo' (pink)<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Perkeo'|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/98049/Astilbe-x-crispa-Perkeo/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|34em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=2&taxon_id=102968 Flora of China: Astilbe]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q159001}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Saxifragaceae]]\n[[Category:Saxifragaceae genera]]\n", "text_old": "{{automatic taxobox\n|image = Astilbe arendsii1.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Astilbe arendsii'' in flower\n|taxon = Astilbe\n|authority = [[Francis Buchanan-Hamilton|Buch.-Ham.]] ex [[David Don|D.Don]]\n|subdivision_ranks = Species\n|subdivision = See text\n|type_species = ''[[Astilbe rivularis]]'' <small>[[Buch.-Ham.]] ex [[D.Don]]</small> \n}}\n\n'''''Astilbe''''' {{IPAc-en|\u0259|\u02c8|s|t|\u026a|l|b|i\u02d0}}<ref>''Sunset Western Garden Book,'' 1995:606\u2013607</ref> is a [[genus]] of 18 [[species]] of [[rhizome|rhizomatous]] [[flowering plant]]s within the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Saxifragaceae]], [[native plant|native]] to mountain ravines and woodlands in Asia and North America.<ref>{{cite book|title=RHS A-Z encyclopedia of garden plants|year=2008|publisher=Dorling Kindersley|location=United Kingdom|isbn=1405332964|pages=1136}}</ref> Some species are known by the common names '''false goat's beard''' and '''false spirea'''.\n\nThese [[hardiness (plants)|hardy]] [[herbaceous]] [[perennial plant|perennials]] are cultivated by gardeners for their large, handsome, often fern-like foliage and dense, feathery plumes of flowers. They are widely adapted to shade and water-logged conditions, hence they are particularly associated with pond-side planting. They also tolerate clay soils well. Numerous [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrid]] [[cultivars]] have been raised. Flowers of at least some ''Astilbe'' species have a strong and pleasant aroma. Some species, including ''[[Astilbe rivularis]]'', are used in traditional medicine.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=O'Neill |first1=Alexander |display-authors=etal |author2= |date=2017-03-29 |title=Integrating ethnobiological knowledge into biodiversity conservation in the Eastern Himalayas |url=https://ethnobiomed.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13002-017-0148-9 |journal=Journal of Ethnobiology and Ethnomedicine |volume=13 |issue=21 |pages= |doi=10.1186/s13002-017-0148-9 |access-date=2017-05-11 |pmc=5372287 |pmid=28356115}}</ref>\n\n==Species==\nSpecies of ''Astilbe'' include:\n*''[[Astilbe biternata]]'' (Vent.) Britt. \n*''[[Astilbe chinensis]]'' (Maxim.) Franch. & Sav.   \n*''[[Astilbe crispa]]'' (Arends) Bergmans \n*''[[Astilbe grandis]]'' Stapf ex E. H. Wilson \u2013 Korean false goat's beard<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.forest.go.kr/kna/special/download/English_Names_for_Korean_Native_Plants.pdf |title=English Names for Korean Native Plants |publisher=[[Korea National Arboretum]] |year=2015 |isbn=978-89-97450-98-5 |location=Pocheon |pages=367 |access-date=24 December 2016 |via=[[Korea Forest Service]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525105020/http://www.forest.go.kr/kna/special/download/English_Names_for_Korean_Native_Plants.pdf |archivedate=25 May 2017 }}</ref>\n*''[[Astilbe japonica]]'' ([[Charles Fran\u00e7ois Antoine Morren|C.Morren]] & Decne.) A.Gray\n*''[[Astilbe longicarpa]]'' (Hayata) Hayata\n*''[[Astilbe macroflora]]'' Hayata \n*''[[Astilbe microphylla]]'' Knoll\n**[[Astilbe microphylla var. riparia|''Astilbe microphylla'' var. ''riparia'']] [[List of botanists by author abbreviation#H|Hatus]]. \n*''[[Astilbe platyphylla]]'' H. Boiss. \n*''[[Astilbe rivularis]]'' Buch.-Ham. ex D. Don \n**[[Astilbe rivularis var. angustifoliolata|''Astilbe rivularis'' var. ''angustifoliolata'']] H. Hara\n**[[Astilbe rivularis var. myriantha|''Astilbe rivularis'' var. ''myriantha'']] (Diels) J. T. Pan \n*''[[Astilbe rubra]]'' Hook. f. & Thomson \u2013 false goat's beard<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''[[Astilbe sikokumontana]]'' Koidz.   \n*''[[Astilbe simplicifolia]]'' Makino \u2013 entire-leaf false goat's beard<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''[[Astilbe thunbergii]]'' (Siebold & Zucc.) Miq.   \n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. congesta|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''congesta'']] H. [[Henri de Boissieu|Boissieu]]\n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. fujisanensis|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''fujisanensis'']] (Nakai) Ohwi \n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. hachijoensis|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''hachijoensis'']] (Nakai) Ohwi \n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. kiusiana|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''kiusiana'']] Hara\n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. longipedicellata|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''longipedicellata'']] Hatus.\n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. okuyamae|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''okuyamae'']] (Hara) [[List of botanists by author abbreviation#O|Ohwi]] \n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. shikokiana|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''shikokiana'']] (Nakai) Ohwi \n**[[Astilbe thunbergii var. terrestris|''Astilbe thunbergii'' var. ''terrestris'']] (Nakai) Ohwi\n\n==Cultivar groups==\nCommonly accepted [[cultivar]] groups are:\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Astilbe Arendsii Group|''Astilbe'' Arendsii Group]]\n*''Astilbe'' Crispa Group\n*''Astilbe'' Japonica Group\n*''Astilbe'' Simplicifolia Group\n{{div col end}}\n\nThe following varieties and cultivars have gained the [[Royal Horticultural Society]]'s [[Award of Garden Merit]]:\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*'Brautschleier' (Arendsii Group) - white<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Brautschleier'|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/112600/Astilbe-Brautschleier-(%25C3%2597-arendsii)/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*'Bronce elegans' (Simplicifolia) - salmon pink<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Bronce Elegans'|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/90688/Astilbe-Bronce-Elegans-(simplicifolia-hybrid)/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*''A. chinensis'' var. ''pumila'' - mauve<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe chinensis'' var. ''pumila''|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/54603/Astilbe-chinensis-var-pumila/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*''A. chinensis'' var. ''taqueti'' 'Superba'<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/89593/Astilbe-chinensis-var-taquetii-Superba/Details | title = ''A. chinensis'' var. taqueti 'Superba' | publisher = RHS | accessdate = 12 April 2020}}</ref> - rose/mauve\n*'Fanal' (Arendsii) - crimson<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Fanal'|url=\nhttps://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/95205/Astilbe-Fanal-(%25C3%2597-arendsii)/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*''A. glaberrima'' var. ''saxatilis'' - pink & white, prostrate<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe glaberrima'' var. ''saxatilis''|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/95706/Astilbe-glaberrima-var-saxatilis/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*'Rheinland' (Japonica) - pale pink<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Rheinland'|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/97102/Astilbe-Rheinland-(japonica-hybrid)/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*''A. simplicifolia''<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe simplicifolia''|url=\nhttps://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/1841/Astilbe-simplicifolia/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*'Sprite' (Simplicifolia) - pale pink<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Sprite'|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/93253/Astilbe-Sprite-(simplicifolia-hybrid)/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*'Straussenfeder' (Thunbergii) - pink<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Straussenfeder'|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/94693/Astilbe-Straussenfeder-(thunbergii-hybrid)/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n*''A.'' \u00d7 ''crispa'' 'Perkeo' (pink)<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Astilbe'' 'Perkeo'|url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/98049/Astilbe-x-crispa-Perkeo/Details | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n{{div col end}}\n\n{{Commonscat|Astilbe}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|34em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=2&taxon_id=102968 Flora of China: Astilbe]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q159001}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Saxifragaceae]]\n[[Category:Saxifragaceae genera]]\n", "name_user": "Darorcilmir", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astilbe"}
{"title_page": "Occupational Pension Funds in the EU", "text_new": "An '''occupational pension fund''', also referred to as an employer funded or employer administered scheme, is a [[pension]] offered by an employer to an employee\u2019s retirement scheme.<ref name=\"OPF\">{{cite web |title=Occupational pension funds |url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/business-economy-euro/banking-and-finance/insurance-and-pensions/occupational-pension-funds_en |website=European Commission |publisher=Directorate-General for Communication |accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref> Within the [[European Union]] (EU), these pension funds can vary throughout certain [[Member state of the European Union|Member States]] due to differences in [[Retirement in Europe|retirement ages in Europe]], salaries and length of careers, labour and tax laws, and phases of reform.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Pension schemes and pension projections in the EU-27 Member States, 2008-2060 |journal=European Economy |date=2009 |volume=1 |issue=56 |pages=28\u201330 |doi=10.2765/54270 |url=https://ec.europa.eu/economy_finance/publications/pages/publication16034_en.pdf |accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis form [[deferred compensation]] can be paid out regularly each month once the employee has retired. It is both beneficial for the employee by saving on taxation and social insurance payments and the employer to attract potential employees and to retain existing as an incentive. It is known as the \u201csecond pillar\u201d of a supplementary pension plan which includes the contribution of employers. This [[free movement of workers]] in the EU allows them to uphold their rights when moving to other Member States.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Davies |first1=Ron |title=Occupational pensions: 'Second pillar' provision in the EU policy context |journal=Library of the European Parliament |date=2013 |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/bibliotheque/briefing/2013/130589/LDM_BRI(2013)130589_REV1_EN.pdf |accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nSince prior to the [[Post\u2013World War II economic expansion|post-World War II period]], European countries embraced a [[State Socialism (Germany)|Bismarckian]] pension system, first introduced in [[Germany]], which allowed retirees to receive benefits from current workers. However, after this period nearly all of Europe had experienced a dramatic increase in life expectancy yet with a decreasing rate of fertility. Since the 1990s, European countries have made attempts to improve their pension systems through various multi-tier pension systems. This typically involved utilizing a combination of mandatory and voluntary schemes where both individuals and the government collectively put money into the system.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gadomski |first1=Witold |title=The end of the Bismarckian model of pensions |url=https://financialobserver.eu/poland/the-end-of-the-bismarckian-model-of-pensions/ |website=Central European Financial Observer |publisher=Narodowy Bank Polski |accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the [[European Commission]] created the International Occupational Pension Funds Directive (also referred to as the IORP Directive) to establish the fundamental requirements of offering occupational pension funds and its regulations.<ref>{{cite journal |title=DIRECTIVE 2003/41/EC OF THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND OF THE COUNCIL of 3 June 2003 on the activities and supervision of institutions for occupational retirement provision |journal=Official Journal of the European Union |date=2003 |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2003:235:0010:0021:EN:PDF |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> However, the IORP was since been revised in 2016 in response to financial crisis since 2008.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Revision of the Occupational Pension Funds Directive |journal=European Commission |date=2016 |issue=16 |url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/sites/info/files/business_economy_euro/banking_and_finance/documents/160701-faq-iorp-directive-revision_en.pdf |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> In addition, pension funds have become one of the EU\u2019s largest expenditures due to increasing pressures from the aging population throughout Europe.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eatock |first1=David |title=European Union pension systems Adequate and sustainable? |journal=European Parliamentary Research Service |date=2015 |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2015/571327/EPRS_BRI%282015%29571327_EN.pdf |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> In 2011, the [[European Parliament]] called upon the Commission to encouraged more Member States to implement occupational pensions for a mix of both public (\u2018first pillar\u2019) and private (\u2018second pillar\u2019) pensions as another step to reform schemes for a more sustainable future.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eatock |first1=David |title=Prospects for occupational pensions in the European Union |journal=European Parliamentary Research Service |date=2015 |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2015/568328/EPRS_BRI(2015)568328_EN.pdf |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> However, the current establishment of occupational pension funds still vary in size and approach across each Member State.\n\nDespite the various designs, occupational pension plans can be defined into two basic types:\n# [[Defined benefit pension plan|Defined benefit (\u2018DB\u2019)]] in which the employee benefit received is calculated through the length of employment under the employer and the specified salary maintained.\n# [[Defined contribution plan|Defined contribution (\u2018DC\u2019)]] where both the employee and employer generate regular contributions into an account. This type of plan is fully funded and are essentially accounts which experience tax-differed savings.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bodie |first1=Zvi |last2=Marcus |first2=Alan J. |last3=Merton |first3=Robert C. |title=Defined Benefit versus Defined Contribution Pension Plans: What are the Real Trade-offs? |journal=Pensions in the U.S. Economy |date=1988 |volume=University of Chicago Press |url=http://www.nber.org/books/bodi88-1 |accessdate=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Reforms and Role of the EU ==\nSince the early 2000s, numerous EU Member States have initiated pension reforms through the adjustment of age requirements and benefits received. These changes were a response to pressures from declining birth rates, increased life expectancies, and aging demographics. With the [[2004 enlargement of the European Union|2004 enlargement of the EU]], \u2018new\u2019 Member States faced challenges to reform their previous pension systems to a market-based from the socialist system.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wagner |first1=Helmut |title=Pension Reform in the New EU Member States: Will a Three-Pillar Pension System Work? |journal=Eastern European Economics |date=2005 |volume=43 |issue=4 |pages=27\u201351 |jstor=4380429 |doi=10.1080/00128775.2005.11041110 }}</ref> However, smaller \u2018new\u2019 EU Member states, such as [[Cyprus]] and [[Slovenia]], began to adopt mandatory occupational pension schemes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Carone |first1=Giuseppe |last2=Eckefeldt |first2=Per |last3=Giamboni |first3=Luigi |last4=Laine |first4=Veli |last5=Sumner |first5=St\u00e9phanie P. |title=Pension Reforms in the EU since the Early 2000s: Achievements and Challenges Ahead |journal=European Economy |date=2016 |doi=10.2765/620267 |url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/sites/info/files/dp042_en.pdf |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> The reform changes made were through toughening conditions of eligibility for earlier retirement age, lessening public pension benefits received, and raising the age of retirement.<ref name=\"David\">{{cite journal |last1=Natali |first1=David |title=Pensions after the financial and economic crisis: a comparative analysis of recent reforms in Europe |journal=ETUI Working Paper 2011.07 |date=2011 |pages=32 |ssrn=2221827 }}</ref>\n\nIn correspondence with the [[Subsidiarity|principle of subsidiarity]], Member States were capable to reform and design their new pension systems. Private pension funds had become a cornerstone part of the EU programme.\n\n=== The International Occupational Pension Funds Directive (IORP) ===\nThe International Occupational Pension Funds Directive was formulated to enhance EU pension funds to meet certain standards regarding financial aspects of occupational pension schemes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=GUARDIANCICH |first1=Igor |last2=NATALI |first2=David |title=The New Pension Mix in Europe |date=2017 |pages=294 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/319939874}}</ref> The revision of this framework for supplementary pension mobility encouraged the enactment of occupational pension funds through long-term investment. Below the revision\u2019s goals included but not limited to:\n# Proper investment requirements to ensure sufficient funds.<ref name=\"OPF\" />\n# Better transparency to each Member State and beneficiary through statements regarding funds received to be properly informed of rights.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Guardiancich |first1=Igor |last2=Natali |first2=David |title=The New Pension Mix in Europe: Recent Reforms, Their Distributional Effects and Political Dynamics |date=2017 |publisher=PIE Peter Lang |url=https://www.peterlang.com/view/9782807602670/chapter09.xhtml |accessdate=1 November 2019|isbn=9782807602670 }}</ref>\n# Elimination of restrictions on occupational pension funds which operate cross borders.<ref name=\"OPF\" />\nThrough the revision, however, it still provides a general framework which is not required to be implemented by all EU Member States. Yet overall, the aim was to guide each institution into [[Harmonisation of law|harmonization]] towards cross-border activity.<ref name=\"SSRN\">{{cite journal |last1=Guardiancich |first1=Igor |last2=Natali |first2=David |title=The EU and Supplementary Pensions: Instruments for Integration and the Market for Occupational Pensions in Europe |journal=SSRN Electronic Journal |date=2011 |ssrn=2264143 }}</ref> The need for the revisions can be attributed towards the pressure for needing to have more retirement savings and occupational pensions due to aging populations and decline in fertility.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Occupational pensions: Revision of the Institutions for Occupational Retirement Provision Directive (IORP II) |journal=European Parliament |date=2016 |volume=Briefing: EU Legislation in Progress |pages=12 |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2016/579101/EPRS_BRI(2016)579101_EN.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== European Integration ==\nOne goal of the European Union can be described as creating an intra-European migration and eliminating restrictions on the [[Labor mobility|mobility of workers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The EU in brief |url=https://europa.eu/european-union/about-eu/eu-in-brief_en |publisher=European Commission |accessdate=1 November 2019|date=2016-06-16 }}</ref> With this goal, originally regulations of pensions schemes were necessary to foster direct and positive integration. In 1998, the EU further became interested in regulations for occupational (supplementary) pension schemes with the Council Directive (98/49) which \nestablished principles to safeguard the pension rights of the movement of EU national workers, maintain equal treatment of EU nationals, and transfer benefits to other Member States.<ref name=\"SSRN\" />\n\nThe European Commission is actively involved to area relating to occupational pension schemes in the EU. The [[Directorate-General for Internal Market, Industry, Entrepreneurship and SMEs|DG Internal Market and Service]] was established to promote the internal market by facilitating [[cross-border cooperation]] in the EU with a basis of rules to follow by.<ref name=\"Blue\">{{cite journal |last1=Tert\u00e1k |first1=Elem\u00e9r |title=The EU internal market for occupational pensions: Making further progress |journal=Pensions: An International Journal |date=2010 |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=140\u2013147 |doi=10.1057/pm.2010.9 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n== Effects from global financial and economic crisis ==\nThe global financial and economic crises following the [[Bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers|2008 Lehman Brothers collapse]] enacted budgetary restrictions in the EU and created vulnerabilities for the pension systems across Member States.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Impavido |first1=Gregorio |last2=Tower |first2=Ian |title=How the Financial Crisis Affects Pensions and Insurance and Why the Impacts Matter |journal=International Monetary Fund |date=2009 |url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/wp/2009/wp09151.pdf |accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref> Both DB and DC plans were significantly affected by the 2008 crisis. On average, throughout countries in the EU with DB plans experienced at least a 10% decrease in benefit cuts.<ref name=\"David\" /> This showed that fully funded pension schemes could not entirely provide a reliable basis for benefits received after retirement.<ref name=\"Blue\" />. Furthermore, during that time with the increase of unemployment made saving for retirement and receiving occupational pension funds more difficult.\n\nWorkers who were nearby their retirement appeared to be affected as well by the crisis.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Pensions in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Pensions in Germany]]\n* [[Pensions in France|Pensions in France]]\n* [[Pensions in the Czech Republic]]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "An '''occupational pension fund''', also referred to as an employer funded or employer administered scheme, is a [[pension]] offered by an employer to an employee\u2019s retirement scheme.<ref name=\"OPF\">{{cite web |title=Occupational pension funds |url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/business-economy-euro/banking-and-finance/insurance-and-pensions/occupational-pension-funds_en |website=European Comission |publisher=Directorate-General for Communication |accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref> Within the [[European Union]] (EU), these pension funds can vary throughout certain [[Member state of the European Union|Member States]] due to differences in [[Retirement in Europe|retirement ages in Europe]], salaries and length of careers, labour and tax laws, and phases of reform.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Pension schemes and pension projections in the EU-27 Member States, 2008-2060 |journal=European Economy |date=2009 |volume=1 |issue=56 |pages=28\u201330 |doi=10.2765/54270 |url=https://ec.europa.eu/economy_finance/publications/pages/publication16034_en.pdf |accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis form [[deferred compensation]] can be paid out regularly each month once the employee has retired. It is both beneficial for the employee by saving on taxation and social insurance payments and the employer to attract potential employees and to retain existing as an incentive. It is known as the \u201csecond pillar\u201d of a supplementary pension plan which includes the contribution of employers. This [[free movement of workers]] in the EU allows them to uphold their rights when moving to other Member States.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Davies |first1=Ron |title=Occupational pensions: 'Second pillar' provision in the EU policy context |journal=Library of the European Parliament |date=2013 |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/bibliotheque/briefing/2013/130589/LDM_BRI(2013)130589_REV1_EN.pdf |accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nSince prior to the [[Post\u2013World War II economic expansion|post-World War II period]], European countries embraced a [[State Socialism (Germany)|Bismarckian]] pension system, first introduced in [[Germany]], which allowed retirees to receive benefits from current workers. However, after this period nearly all of Europe had experienced a dramatic increase in life expectancy yet with a decreasing rate of fertility. Since the 1990s, European countries have made attempts to improve their pension systems through various multi-tier pension systems. This typically involved utilizing a combination of mandatory and voluntary schemes where both individuals and the government collectively put money into the system.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gadomski |first1=Witold |title=The end of the Bismarckian model of pensions |url=https://financialobserver.eu/poland/the-end-of-the-bismarckian-model-of-pensions/ |website=Central European Financial Observer |publisher=Narodowy Bank Polski |accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the [[European Commission]] created the International Occupational Pension Funds Directive (also referred to as the IORP Directive) to establish the fundamental requirements of offering occupational pension funds and its regulations.<ref>{{cite journal |title=DIRECTIVE 2003/41/EC OF THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND OF THE COUNCIL of 3 June 2003 on the activities and supervision of institutions for occupational retirement provision |journal=Official Journal of the European Union |date=2003 |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2003:235:0010:0021:EN:PDF |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> However, the IORP was since been revised in 2016 in response to financial crisis since 2008.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Revision of the Occupational Pension Funds Directive |journal=European Comission |date=2016 |issue=16 |url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/sites/info/files/business_economy_euro/banking_and_finance/documents/160701-faq-iorp-directive-revision_en.pdf |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> In addition, pension funds have become one of the EU\u2019s largest expenditures due to increasing pressures from the aging population throughout Europe.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eatock |first1=David |title=European Union pension systems Adequate and sustainable? |journal=European Parliamentary Research Service |date=2015 |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2015/571327/EPRS_BRI%282015%29571327_EN.pdf |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> In 2011, the [[European Parliament]] called upon the Commission to encouraged more Member States to implement occupational pensions for a mix of both public (\u2018first pillar\u2019) and private (\u2018second pillar\u2019) pensions as another step to reform schemes for a more sustainable future.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eatock |first1=David |title=Prospects for occupational pensions in the European Union |journal=European Parliamentary Research Service |date=2015 |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2015/568328/EPRS_BRI(2015)568328_EN.pdf |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> However, the current establishment of occupational pension funds still vary in size and approach across each Member State.\n\nDespite the various designs, occupational pension plans can be defined into two basic types:\n# [[Defined benefit pension plan|Defined benefit (\u2018DB\u2019)]] in which the employee benefit received is calculated through the length of employment under the employer and the specified salary maintained.\n# [[Defined contribution plan|Defined contribution (\u2018DC\u2019)]] where both the employee and employer generate regular contributions into an account. This type of plan is fully funded and are essentially accounts which experience tax-differed savings.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bodie |first1=Zvi |last2=Marcus |first2=Alan J. |last3=Merton |first3=Robert C. |title=Defined Benefit versus Defined Contribution Pension Plans: What are the Real Trade-offs? |journal=Pensions in the U.S. Economy |date=1988 |volume=University of Chicago Press |url=http://www.nber.org/books/bodi88-1 |accessdate=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Reforms and Role of the EU ==\nSince the early 2000s, numerous EU Member States have initiated pension reforms through the adjustment of age requirements and benefits received. These changes were a response to pressures from declining birth rates, increased life expectancies, and aging demographics. With the [[2004 enlargement of the European Union|2004 enlargement of the EU]], \u2018new\u2019 Member States faced challenges to reform their previous pension systems to a market-based from the socialist system.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wagner |first1=Helmut |title=Pension Reform in the New EU Member States: Will a Three-Pillar Pension System Work? |journal=Eastern European Economics |date=2005 |volume=43 |issue=4 |pages=27\u201351 |jstor=4380429 |doi=10.1080/00128775.2005.11041110 }}</ref> However, smaller \u2018new\u2019 EU Member states, such as [[Cyprus]] and [[Slovenia]], began to adopt mandatory occupational pension schemes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Carone |first1=Giuseppe |last2=Eckefeldt |first2=Per |last3=Giamboni |first3=Luigi |last4=Laine |first4=Veli |last5=Sumner |first5=St\u00e9phanie P. |title=Pension Reforms in the EU since the Early 2000s: Achievements and Challenges Ahead |journal=European Economy |date=2016 |doi=10.2765/620267 |url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/sites/info/files/dp042_en.pdf |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> The reform changes made were through toughening conditions of eligibility for earlier retirement age, lessening public pension benefits received, and raising the age of retirement.<ref name=\"David\">{{cite journal |last1=Natali |first1=David |title=Pensions after the financial and economic crisis: a comparative analysis of recent reforms in Europe |journal=ETUI Working Paper 2011.07 |date=2011 |pages=32 |ssrn=2221827 }}</ref>\n\nIn correspondence with the [[Subsidiarity|principle of subsidiarity]], Member States were capable to reform and design their new pension systems. Private pension funds had become a cornerstone part of the EU programme.\n\n=== The International Occupational Pension Funds Directive (IORP) ===\nThe International Occupational Pension Funds Directive was formulated to enhance EU pension funds to meet certain standards regarding financial aspects of occupational pension schemes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=GUARDIANCICH |first1=Igor |last2=NATALI |first2=David |title=The New Pension Mix in Europe |date=2017 |pages=294 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/319939874}}</ref> The revision of this framework for supplementary pension mobility encouraged the enactment of occupational pension funds through long-term investment. Below the revision\u2019s goals included but not limited to:\n# Proper investment requirements to ensure sufficient funds.<ref name=\"OPF\" />\n# Better transparency to each Member State and beneficiary through statements regarding funds received to be properly informed of rights.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Guardiancich |first1=Igor |last2=Natali |first2=David |title=The New Pension Mix in Europe: Recent Reforms, Their Distributional Effects and Political Dynamics |date=2017 |publisher=PIE Peter Lang |url=https://www.peterlang.com/view/9782807602670/chapter09.xhtml |accessdate=1 November 2019|isbn=9782807602670 }}</ref>\n# Elimination of restrictions on occupational pension funds which operate cross borders.<ref name=\"OPF\" />\nThrough the revision, however, it still provides a general framework which is not required to be implemented by all EU Member States. Yet overall, the aim was to guide each institution into [[Harmonisation of law|harmonization]] towards cross-border activity.<ref name=\"SSRN\">{{cite journal |last1=Guardiancich |first1=Igor |last2=Natali |first2=David |title=The EU and Supplementary Pensions: Instruments for Integration and the Market for Occupational Pensions in Europe |journal=SSRN Electronic Journal |date=2011 |ssrn=2264143 }}</ref> The need for the revisions can be attributed towards the pressure for needing to have more retirement savings and occupational pensions due to aging populations and decline in fertility.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Occupational pensions: Revision of the Institutions for Occupational Retirement Provision Directive (IORP II) |journal=European Parliament |date=2016 |volume=Briefing: EU Legislation in Progress |pages=12 |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2016/579101/EPRS_BRI(2016)579101_EN.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== European Integration ==\nOne goal of the European Union can be described as creating an intra-European migration and eliminating restrictions on the [[Labor mobility|mobility of workers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The EU in brief |url=https://europa.eu/european-union/about-eu/eu-in-brief_en |publisher=European Commission |accessdate=1 November 2019|date=2016-06-16 }}</ref> With this goal, originally regulations of pensions schemes were necessary to foster direct and positive integration. In 1998, the EU further became interested in regulations for occupational (supplementary) pension schemes with the Council Directive (98/49) which \nestablished principles to safeguard the pension rights of the movement of EU national workers, maintain equal treatment of EU nationals, and transfer benefits to other Member States.<ref name=\"SSRN\" />\n\nThe European Commission is actively involved to area relating to occupational pension schemes in the EU. The [[Directorate-General for Internal Market, Industry, Entrepreneurship and SMEs|DG Internal Market and Service]] was established to promote the internal market by facilitating [[cross-border cooperation]] in the EU with a basis of rules to follow by.<ref name=\"Blue\">{{cite journal |last1=Tert\u00e1k |first1=Elem\u00e9r |title=The EU internal market for occupational pensions: Making further progress |journal=Pensions: An International Journal |date=2010 |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=140\u2013147 |doi=10.1057/pm.2010.9 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n== Effects from global financial and economic crisis ==\nThe global financial and economic crises following the [[Bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers|2008 Lehman Brothers collapse]] enacted budgetary restrictions in the EU and created vulnerabilities for the pension systems across Member States.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Impavido |first1=Gregorio |last2=Tower |first2=Ian |title=How the Financial Crisis Affects Pensions and Insurance and Why the Impacts Matter |journal=International Monetary Fund |date=2009 |url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/wp/2009/wp09151.pdf |accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref> Both DB and DC plans were significantly affected by the 2008 crisis. On average, throughout countries in the EU with DB plans experienced at least a 10% decrease in benefit cuts.<ref name=\"David\" /> This showed that fully funded pension schemes could not entirely provide a reliable basis for benefits received after retirement.<ref name=\"Blue\" />. Furthermore, during that time with the increase of unemployment made saving for retirement and receiving occupational pension funds more difficult.\n\nWorkers who were nearby their retirement appeared to be affected as well by the crisis.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Pensions in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Pensions in Germany]]\n* [[Pensions in France|Pensions in France]]\n* [[Pensions in the Czech Republic]]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Klbrain", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occupational_Pension_Funds_in_the_EU"}
