ton |title=East Boston Post Office |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher=United States Post Office |accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Logan Office Center, which contains the headquarters of the [[Massachusetts Port Authority]], is adjacent to [[Logan Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.massport.com |title=Massport Homepage |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher=MassPort |accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\n{{Main|Boston#Education}}\n\n==== Primary and secondary schools ====\n===== Public schools =====\n[[Boston Public Schools]] operates numerous schools in East Boston.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bostonpublicschools.org/view/all-schools-z |title=All Schools (A-Z) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no byline.--> |date= |website= |publisher=Boston Public Schools |accessdate=March 18, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423073046/http://www.bostonpublicschools.org/view/all-schools-z |archive-date=April 23, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> BPS assigns students based on student preference and priorities of students in various zones. Due to the geography of East Boston, every child in the neighborhood is guaranteed a seat at a school in East Boston. The district instructs parents wanting to send their children to East Boston schools to place East Boston campuses on their school assignment priority lists higher than non-neighborhood campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bostonpublicschools.org/assignment |title=Student Assignment Policy: East Boston Assignments |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher=Boston Public Schools |accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nEast Boston Early Childhood Center is a district K0\u20131 school in East Boston. District elementary schools include Samuel Adams, Manassah E. Bradley, Curtis Guild, Patrick J. Kennedy, Hugh R. O'Donnell, and James Otis.\n\nMario Umana Academy and Donald McKay K-8 School are the two district K\u20138 schools in East Boston. [[East Boston High School]] is the sole district public high school in East Boston.\n\nExcel Academy Charter School, a [[charter school|charter middle school]], is located on Moore St. in East Boston.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.excelacademy.org/ |title=Excel Academy |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher=Excel Academy |accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n<div align=center><gallery perrow=4 widths=200px heights=150px>\nFile:East Boston High School (1).jpg|[[East Boston High School]]\nFile:Samuel Adams Elementary School (2).jpg|Samuel Adams Elementary School\nFile:Manassah E. Bradley Elementary School (2).jpg|Manassah E. Bradley Elementary School\nFile:Curtis Guild Elementary School (1).jpg|Curtis Guild Elementary School\nFile:Patrick J. Kennedy Elementary School.jpg|Patrick J. Kennedy Elementary School\nFile:Donald McKay K-8 School (1).jpg|Donald McKay K-8 School\nFile:Hugh R. O'Donnell Elementary School (1).jpg|Hugh R. O'Donnell Elementary School\nFile:James Otis Elementary School (1).jpg|James Otis Elementary School\n</gallery></div>\n\n===== Private schools =====\nIn spring 1892, a school named after [[James Fitton (priest)|Fr. James Fitton]] was dedicated on the Holy Redeemer site. In 1974, a school merger occurred, producing the current East Boston Central Catholic School.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ebccs.org/GenInfo.htm |title=East Boston Central Catholic - EBCCS |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |publisher=East Boston Central Catholic |accessdate=March 18, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727233350/http://www.ebccs.org/GenInfo.htm |archive-date=July 27, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Boston]] operates East Boston Central Catholic School on the Most Holy Redeemer Parish site.  It is a K1\u20138 private school in East Boston. The school is managed by a board from the Our Lady of the Assumption, [[Our Lady of Mount Carmel Church (East Boston)|Our Lady of Mount Carmel]], Most Holy Redeemer and Sacred Heart parishes.\n\nIn Spring 2008, the Archdiocese ordered the closure of St. Mary, Star of the Sea School, a K\u20138 school in East Boston. The parish attached to the school had closed three years prior to the closure of the school.<ref>{{cite news |title=Church to Sell St. Mary's Star of the Sea Building |author=Jeremy C. Fox |url=http://www.boston.com/yourtown/news/east_boston/2011/01/church_to_sell_former_school_b.html |newspaper=Boston.com |date=January 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nUntil it closed in 2007, [[Savio Preparatory High School]] was a private, coeducational high school in East Boston.<ref>{{cite news |title=Savio Prep Students and Parents Prep for Closing |author=Stephanie Ebbert |url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/city_region/breaking_news/2007/03/savio_prep_stud.html |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=March 2, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==== Public libraries ====\n[[File:Orient Heights Branch, Boston Public Library (2).jpg|thumb|left|250px|The former [[Orient Heights]] branch of the [[Boston Public Library]].]]\n\nThe first public branch library in the United States was established in East Boston in 1870.<ref name=x>{{cite web| url=https://www.boston.gov/neighborhood/east-boston|title=East Boston |publisher=City of Boston |date=April 3, 2017|accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>  [[Boston Public Library]] currently has one location in East Boston, at [http://www.bpl.org/branches/eastboston.htm 365 Bremen Street] in the Bremen Street Park. This branch opened in November 2013. The old branches at 276 Meridian Street and 18 Barnes Avenue were closed in 2013, shortly before the current branch opened.\n\n=== Community resources ===\nEast Boston has a wide variety of community resources, both not-for-profit and government-funded.\n\n=== Community centers ===\nThe City of Boston runs two community centers in East Boston: Orient Heights Community Center (now called The Marcintino Community Center) and Paris Street Community Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/myneighborhood/?pid=0100079000|title=My Neighborhood - City of Boston|publisher=|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref>  These Centers are an initiative of a citywide organization called Boston Center for Youth and Families.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston Centers for Youth & Families|url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/BCYF/|website=cityofboston.gov|accessdate=2014|ref=4}}</ref> The Centers aim to assist local youth with after-school programming.\n\n=== Open space ===\nIn the early 1990s, East Boston had the least open space of any Boston neighborhood, except Chinatown.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} However, the city of Boston, and East Boston in particular, has undergone several major initiatives to increase open space in Boston.  One such initiative is called Urban Wilds.  Unveiled in 2016, it focuses on protecting \"urban wilds\" in Boston's neighborhoods.  The city has identified four sites in Boston which it is targeting to improve coastal habitats, rejuvenate fish populations, restore soil, and use for flood control and water quality improvement purposes.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.boston.gov/departments/parks-and-recreation/urban-wilds-east-boston |title=Urban Wilds: East Boston |website= Department of Parks and Recreation |publisher=City of Boston | date=July 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe city's creation of the [[East Boston Greenway]], which stretches from the wharfs at Maverick Square to the Bayswater Urban Wild, has also been a major addition to the neighborhood's green space.\n\nToday, East Boston has 230 acres of protected open space, and 371 acres of total open space.  This averages out to 5.98 acres of protected space per thousand individuals.  This is less than the citywide average of 7.43 acres per thousand people.<ref name=open>{{Cite report |author=Boston Parks and Recreation Department  |date= |title=Community Open Space & Recreation Mission: The Neighborhoods |url=https://www.cityofboston.gov/parks/pdfs/os3f.pdf |publisher=City of Boston |page=102 |docket= |accessdate=May 30, 2017 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n=== Housing ===\nUp until 2011 there were a total of 16,090 housing units in East Boston.  Of these, 14,832 were occupied and 1,258 were vacant. Out of the 14,832 occupied units, 4,248 were owner-occupied and 10,584 were renter-occupied. The median gross rent was $1,092.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bostonredevelopmentauthority.org/getattachment/c6b4a4f7-ed70-40a0-ace9-58874ac79df5|title=East Boston Neighborhood|last=Melnik|first=Mark|last2=Gao|first2=Lingshan|date=May 2013|website=American Community Survey|publisher=Boston Redevelopment Authority|access-date=April 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHomelessness is an issue in the shelters and on the streets of East Boston.  To help families transition out of East Boston's homeless shelter, the City of Boston, Crossroads Family Shelter, and the East Boston Community Development Corporation joined together in 2015 create [[subsidized housing]] on Havre Street.  There are seven new affordable units planned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eastietimes.com/2015/11/26/city-east-boston-cdc-cut-ribbon-on-housing-for-the-homeless/|title=City, East Boston CDC Cut Ribbon on Housing for the Homeless|last=Lynds|first=John|date=November 26, 2015|website=East Boston Times-Free Press|publisher=Eastie Times|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Transportation ==\n[[File:Eastern Terminus of Interstate 90 Close-Up.JPG|left|thumb|250px|The eastern terminus of I-90 in East Boston]]\nTransportation has long played a role in the shaping of East Boston. [[Clipper ships]] were built at the shipyard owned by [[Donald McKay]] in the mid-19th century. A [[rapid transit|subway]] tunnel connecting the neighborhood to the rest of the city opened in 1904 and was the first [[undersea tunnel]] of its kind in the United States.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} Rows of houses were torn down to build the Sumner Tunnel in 1934 and the Callahan Tunnel in 1961, directly connecting automobile traffic from downtown Boston. In the early 1920s, an airfield was built, and eventually it was expanded to become Logan International Airport. The eastern terminus of [[Interstate 90]] (the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]]) has been at [[Massachusetts Route 1A|Route 1A]] next to Logan Airport since 2003, and the newer [[Ted Williams Tunnel]] (1995) links I-90 from East Boston to the rest of the city.\n\nLogan Airport, New England's primary international airport and [[World's busiest airports by passenger traffic|48th busiest in the world]], resides mainly in East Boston (though part of the airfield itself lies in [[Winthrop, Massachusetts|Winthrop]]). There has been continual controversy surrounding Logan, as constant conflict with the [[Massachusetts Port Authority]] has been a source of bitterness among some local residents since its inception.{{According to whom|date=August 2017}} One expansion of the Airport resulted in the loss of Wood Island Park, a green space designed by the noted landscape architect [[Frederick Law Olmsted]]. The expansion of Logan Airport in the late 1960s and early 1970s displaced families along [[Neptune Road]], which is now used for warehouses and rental car property. The airport has since implemented four \"airport edge buffers,\" which include parks and greenery to appease residents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.massport.com/news-room/News/BufferNeptuneRoad.aspx |title=Airport Edge Buffer Project Planned for Neptune Road |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 11, 2009 |publisher=MassPort |accessdate=March 18, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728024959/http://www.massport.com/news-room/News/BufferNeptuneRoad.aspx |archive-date=July 28, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe neighborhood is easily accessible to downtown Boston via the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority|MBTA]] [[Blue Line (MBTA)|Blue Line]].\nThe MBTA's [[Blue Line (MBTA)|Blue Line]] stops in East Boston include [[Maverick (MBTA station)|Maverick]], [[Airport (MBTA station)|Airport]], [[Wood Island (MBTA station)|Wood Island]], [[Orient Heights (MBTA station)|Orient Heights]], and [[Suffolk Downs (MBTA station)|Suffolk Downs]]. Massport provides free shuttle buses from the Airport MBTA station to all Logan Airport terminals and the Rental Car Center. The [[East Boston Greenway]], a [[shared use path]] and park along a former rail line, connects to the Airport station.\n\n== Notable people ==\nSee also [[:Category:People from East Boston, Boston|People from East Boston, Boston]]\n*[[Benjamin A. Botkin]], scholar and [[folklorist]]\n*[[Thomas J. Buckley]], 18th [[Massachusetts Auditor]]\n*[[John J. Douglass]], member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1925\u20131933\n*[[Frank Greer]], rower and [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] gold medalist\n*[[Helen Johns (swimmer)|Helen Johns]], swimmer and Olympic gold medalist\n*[[Augie Lio]], former [[American football]] player and member of the [[College Football Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Frederick Mansfield]], 46th [[Mayor of Boston]]\n*[[James O'Grady]], Founder of the [[Boston]] [[Typewriter]] [[Orchestra]]\n*[[William Matthew Prior]], noted [[painter]]\n*[[Gene Sharp]], scholar\n*[[Robert Travaglini]], 93rd [[President of the Massachusetts Senate]]\n*[[Jermaine Wiggins]], former [[American football]] player and [[Super Bowl XXXVI]] champion\n*[[John L. Bates]], 41st [[Governor of Massachusetts]]\n*[[P.J. Kennedy]], Massachusetts politician and grandfather of U.S. President [[John F. Kennedy]].\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Central Square, East Boston, Massachusetts|Central Square]]\n*[[Day Square]]\n*[[Eagle Hill Historic District|Eagle Hill]]\n*[[Maverick Square]]\n*[[Orient Heights]]\n* [[Italian Americans in Boston]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* G. Gibbs, Jr., ''[https://archive.org/details/eastbostonsurvey00bost East Boston: A Survey and a Comprehensive Plan]'', City Planning Board of Boston, 1915.  A historic overview.\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|East Boston}}\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Boston/East Boston|East Boston}}\n* [http://www.eastboston.com EastBoston.com]\n* [http://www.cityofboston.gov/neighborhoods/eastboston.asp City of Boston profile]\n* [http://www.eastietimes.com/ East Boston Times-Free Press]\n* [https://globalboston.bc.edu/index.php/home/immigrant-places/east-boston/ Global Boston: East Boston]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hAFKCTUmAHA|East Boston Immigration Station (YouTube)]\n\n{{BostonMA}}\n{{Coord|42|22|30|N|71|02|21|W|type:city_region:US-MA|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Boston]]\n[[Category:East Boston]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American culture in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Italian-American culture in Boston]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Sicklemoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePiers Park", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Boston"}
{"title_page": "Evangelical Christian School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n|name              = Evangelical Christian School\n|image             = Evangelical Christian School logo.JPG\n|imagesize         = 100px\n|caption           = \n|location          =\n|streetaddress     = 7600 Macon Road\n|city              = [[Cordova, Tennessee|Cordova]]\n|state             = [[Tennessee]]\n|zipcode           = 38018\n|country           = \n| coordinates             =  {{Coord|35.1529194|-89.8123787|display=inline}} \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| pushpin_map             = Tennessee\n|telephone         =\n|fax               =\n|email             =\n|religion          = [[Non-denominational Christian]]\n|denomination      =\n|president         = Braxton Brady\n|headmaster        =\n|roll              =\n|MOE               =\n|ceeb              = 430453\n|school code       =\n|LEA               =\n|ofsted            =\n|testaverage       =\n|national_ranking  =\n|classrooms        =\n|class             =\n|classes offered   =\n|avg_class_size    =\n|ratio             =\n|SAT               =\n|ACT               =\n|graduates         =\n|schooltype        = Private co-educational [[Primary education|Primary]] and [[Secondary Education|Secondary]] school\n|enrollment        = \n|campuses          = Shelby Farms and Lower School\n|campus size       =\n|campus type       =\n|hours_in_day      =\n|athletics         =\n|conference        =\n|slogan            =\n|song              = \"May the Mind of Christ\"\n|fightsong         =\n|motto             = ''Pursuit of Excellence for the Glory of God''\n|accreditation     =\n|rival             =\n|uniform           =\n|nickname          = Eagles\n|sports            =\n|school_colors     = Cardinal and White {{Color box|maroon|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|white|border=darkgray}}\n|yearbook          = Ichthus\n|publication       =\n|newspaper         = The Eagle's Eye\n|opened            =\n|established       =\n|founded           = 1965\n|footnotes         =\n|picture           =\n|website           = ecseagles.com\n}}\n\n'''Evangelical Christian School''', also known as '''ECS''', is a [[private school|private]], [[non-denominational]], [[Evangelicalism|evangelical]] [[Christian school]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]. It was founded in 1965 and joined [[Association of Christian Schools International]] in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acsi.org/web2003/default.aspx?ID=2065&ConstitID=0032900 |title=ACSI.org-ECS|access-date=2007-05-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928100215/https://www.acsi.org/web2003/default.aspx?ID=2065&ConstitID=0032900|archive-date=2007-09-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> It hosts grades K-2 to 12, with grades K-2 through 5th grade at the Lower School campus in Germantown, TN and grades 6-12 at the Shelby Farms campus in Cordova, TN.\n\n==History==\nECS was established in 1965 as a result of praying parents who wanted a Christian education based on biblical principles for their children. \n==Campuses==\n\n=== Lower School (Forest Hill)===\nThe Lower School campus hosts students  in grades K-2 through 5th. The faculty teach students in a variety of disciplines such as science, math, English and literature, history, and Bible study. Additional course offerings are available, such as art, physical education, music, and Spanish.\n\nIn addition to the daily scheduled activities, the schools hold a weekly chapel service. A speaker delivers a message to the students about a Bible lessons.\n\n===Shelby Farms===\nThe Shelby Farms campus includes the [[middle school]] and upper school campuses. Although they are on the same grounds, the middle school and high school students are taught in separate buildings; they also have separate principals, teachers, and lunch times. The [[middle school]] grades consist of grades 6 through 8. These students are taught math, science, Bible, geography, English, literature, and many other subjects.\n\n==Athletics==\n{{more citations needed section|date=April 2018}}\nEvangelical Christian School's mascot is the [[eagle]], with team colors of cardinal and white. ECS is in the Division 2 (private schools) of the [[Tennessee Secondary School Athletic Association]].\nECS participates in football, soccer, baseball, softball, swimming, track and field, cross country running, tennis, basketball, lacrosse, trap, and golf.\n\nECS has won a total of 25 State championships in 9 different sports:\nBaseball 1986, 1996, 1998, 2011, 2013, 2017\nFootball 1983, 1999, 2000, 2005, 2019\nBoys Golf 1995, 2009, 2012\nBoys Soccer 2010, 2011, 2019\nBoys Decathlon 2010, 2011\nBoys Basketball 2011\nGirls Soccer 2015, 2016\nGirls Track 1981, 2010, 2014\nVolleyball 2009\n\nThe Boys Soccer team won back-to-back State Championships defeating [[Jackson Christian School]] 2-0 on May 27, 2010, and [[University School of Nashville]] 2-0 on May 26, 2011. On May 23, 2019, ECS defeated [[Christ Presbyterian Academy]] 3-0 to capture its third championship. They ended the season nationally ranked with a record of 18-0-2.\n\nThe ECS boys basketball team claimed the school's first state championship on March 5, 2011.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Brad Cottam]],<ref name=\"ECS Legacy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ecseagles.com/athletics/legacy-athletes |title=Legacy Athletes - Evangelical Christian School|website=www.ecseagles.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/cottam_brad00.html|title=University of Tennessee Athletics| website=www.utsports.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://cfn.scout.com/a.z?s=451&p=8&c=1&nid=270167|title=NFL, College Sports, NBA and Recruiting|website=scout.com}}</ref> professional football player, [[Kansas City Chiefs]]\n*[[Morgan Cox]],<ref name=\"ECS Legacy\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoreravens.com/team/roster/Morgan-Cox/61f731d9-d6e7-4778-aa49-f3b874747bb0|title=Morgan Cox|website=www.baltimoreravens.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/cox_morgan00.html|title=University of Tennessee Athletics|website=www.utsports.com}}</ref> professional football player, [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n*[[Drew Holcomb]],<ref name=\"Brightly\">{{cite news|last1=Horrocks|first1=Melissa|title=ECS Still Shining Brightly After 50 Years| url=https://www.pressreader.com/usa/the-commercial-appeal/20150915/286461437264842|accessdate=9 December 2017|work=The Commercial Appeal| date=15 September 2015}}</ref> musician\n*[[Barrett Jones]],<ref name=\"ECS Legacy\" /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/12/in_tide_star_barrett_jones_fam.html|title=In Tide star Barrett Jones' family, football hasn't come first|publisher=}}</ref><ref>http://www.commercialappeal.com/sports/preps/first-and-10-who-are-the-best-memphians-to-play-sec-football-ep-1249569457-327932821.html</ref> professional football player\n*[[Spencer Pulley]], professional football player, [[Los Angeles Chargers]]\n*[[Brent Rooker]], professional baseball player, [[Minnesota Twins]]\n*[[George Sherrill]],<ref name=\"ECS Legacy\" /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/baltimore-orioles-closer-george-sherrill-is-making-a-name-for-himself/article/45771|title=Baltimore Orioles closer George Sherrill is making a name for himself|date=27 July 2008|publisher=}}</ref> pitcher, [[Atlanta Braves]], [[Los Angeles Dodgers]]\n*[[Skal Labissi\u00e8re]], professional basketball player, [[Portland Trail Blazers]]\n*[[Christopher Daniel Duntsch]],<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.dmagazine.com/publications/d-magazine/2016/november/christopher-duntsch-dr-death/|title=Dr. Death: The Shocking Story of a Madman with a Scalpel}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/272320662/Christopher-Duntsch-Indictments| title=Christopher Duntsch Indictments}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.commercialappeal.com/story/news/2018/10/24/dr-death-podcast-christopher-duntsch-memphis-ut-health-science-center/1739766002/|title=Disgraced surgeon in 'Dr. Death' podcast grew up in Memphis, trained at UT Health Science Center}}</ref> AKA \"Dr. Death\", former neurosurgeon, serving life sentence for gross malpractice resulting in the death and maiming of multiple patients.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://ecseagles.com/ Evangelical Christian School]\n\n[[Category:Christian schools in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Nondenominational Christian schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Schools in Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Segregation academies in Tennessee]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n|name              = Evangelical Christian School\n|image             = Evangelical Christian School logo.JPG\n|imagesize         = 100px\n|caption           = \n|location          =\n|streetaddress     = 7600 Macon Road\n|city              = [[Cordova, Tennessee|Cordova]]\n|state             = [[Tennessee]]\n|zipcode           = 38018\n|country           = \n| coordinates             =  {{Coord|35.1529194|-89.8123787|display=inline}} \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| pushpin_map             = Tennessee\n|telephone         =\n|fax               =\n|email             =\n|religion          = [[Non-denominational Christian]]\n|denomination      =\n|president         = Braxton Brady\n|headmaster        =\n|roll              =\n|MOE               =\n|ceeb              = 430453\n|school code       =\n|LEA               =\n|ofsted            =\n|testaverage       =\n|national_ranking  =\n|classrooms        =\n|class             =\n|classes offered   =\n|avg_class_size    =\n|ratio             =\n|SAT               =\n|ACT               =\n|graduates         =\n|schooltype        = Private co-educational [[Primary education|Primary]] and [[Secondary Education|Secondary]] school\n|enrollment        = \n|campuses          = Shelby Farms and Lower School\n|campus size       =\n|campus type       =\n|hours_in_day      =\n|athletics         =\n|conference        =\n|slogan            =\n|song              = \"May the Mind of Christ\"\n|fightsong         =\n|motto             = ''Pursuit of Excellence for the Glory of God''\n|accreditation     =\n|rival             =\n|uniform           =\n|nickname          = Eagles\n|sports            =\n|school_colors     = Cardinal and White {{Color box|maroon|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|white|border=darkgray}}\n|yearbook          = Ichthus\n|publication       =\n|newspaper         = The Eagle's Eye\n|opened            =\n|established       =\n|founded           = 1965\n|footnotes         =\n|picture           =\n|website           = ecseagles.com\n}}\n\n'''Evangelical Christian School''', also known as '''ECS''', is a [[private school|private]], [[non-denominational]], [[Evangelicalism|evangelical]] [[Christian school]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]. It was founded in 1965 and joined [[Association of Christian Schools International]] in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acsi.org/web2003/default.aspx?ID=2065&ConstitID=0032900 |title=ACSI.org-ECS|access-date=2007-05-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928100215/https://www.acsi.org/web2003/default.aspx?ID=2065&ConstitID=0032900|archive-date=2007-09-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> It hosts grades Pre-K to 12, with grades Pre-K through 5th grade at the Lower School campus in Germantown, TN and grades 6-12 at the Macon campus in Cordova, TN.\n\n==History==\nECS was established in 1965 as part of a [[Segregation academy|wave of private schools]] formed by white parents in response to [[desegregation busing]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lUc1MkdSp4EC&pg=PA85|title=Opportunity Lost: Race and Poverty in the Memphis City Schools |last=Pohlmann| first=Marcus D.|author-link=Marcus Pohlmann|date=2008|publisher=Univ. of Tennessee Press| isbn=9781572336384| language=en|page=85}}</ref>\n\n==Campuses==\n\n=== Lower School (Forest Hill)===\nThe Lower School campus hosts students  in grades Pre-K through 5th. The faculty teach students in a variety of disciplines such as science, math, English and literature, history, and Bible study. Additional course offerings are available, such as art, physical education, music, and Spanish.\n\nIn addition to the daily scheduled activities, the schools hold a weekly chapel service. A speaker delivers a message to the students about a Bible lessons.\n\n===Shelby Farms===\nThe Shelby Farms campus includes the [[middle school]] and upper school campuses. Although they are on the same grounds, the middle school and high school students are taught in separate buildings; they also have separate principals, teachers, and lunch times. The [[middle school]] grades consist of grades 6 through 8. These students are taught math, science, Bible, geography, English, literature, and many other subjects.\n\n==Athletics==\n{{more citations needed section|date=April 2018}}\nEvangelical Christian School's mascot is the [[eagle]], with team colors of cardinal and white. ECS is in the Division 2 (private schools) of the [[Tennessee Secondary School Athletic Association]].\nECS participates in football, soccer, baseball, softball, swimming, track and field, cross country running, tennis, basketball, lacrosse, trap, and golf.\n\nECS has won a total of 25 State championships in 9 different sports:\nBaseball 1986, 1996, 1998, 2011, 2013, 2017\nFootball 1983, 1999, 2000, 2005, 2019\nBoys Golf 1995, 2009, 2012\nBoys Soccer 2010, 2011, 2019\nBoys Decathlon 2010, 2011\nBoys Basketball 2011\nGirls Soccer 2015, 2016\nGirls Track 1981, 2010, 2014\nVolleyball 2009\n\nThe Boys Soccer team won back to back State Championships defeating [[Jackson Christian School]] 2-0 on May 27, 2010, and [[University School of Nashville]] 2-0 on May 26, 2011. On May 23, 2019, ECS defeated [[Christ Presbyterian Academy]] 3-0 to capture its third championship. They ended the season nationally ranked with a record of 18-0-2.\n\nThe ECS boys basketball team claimed the school's first state championship on March 5, 2011.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Brad Cottam]],<ref name=\"ECS Legacy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ecseagles.com/athletics/legacy-athletes |title=Legacy Athletes - Evangelical Christian School|website=www.ecseagles.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/cottam_brad00.html|title=University of Tennessee Athletics| website=www.utsports.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://cfn.scout.com/a.z?s=451&p=8&c=1&nid=270167|title=NFL, College Sports, NBA and Recruiting|website=scout.com}}</ref> professional football player, [[Kansas City Chiefs]]\n*[[Morgan Cox]],<ref name=\"ECS Legacy\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoreravens.com/team/roster/Morgan-Cox/61f731d9-d6e7-4778-aa49-f3b874747bb0|title=Morgan Cox|website=www.baltimoreravens.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/cox_morgan00.html|title=University of Tennessee Athletics|website=www.utsports.com}}</ref> professional football player, [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n*[[Drew Holcomb]],<ref name=\"Brightly\">{{cite news|last1=Horrocks|first1=Melissa|title=ECS Still Shining Brightly After 50 Years| url=https://www.pressreader.com/usa/the-commercial-appeal/20150915/286461437264842|accessdate=9 December 2017|work=The Commercial Appeal| date=15 September 2015}}</ref> musician\n*[[Barrett Jones]],<ref name=\"ECS Legacy\" /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/12/in_tide_star_barrett_jones_fam.html|title=In Tide star Barrett Jones' family, football hasn't come first|publisher=}}</ref><ref>http://www.commercialappeal.com/sports/preps/first-and-10-who-are-the-best-memphians-to-play-sec-football-ep-1249569457-327932821.html</ref> professional football player\n*[[Spencer Pulley]], professional football player, [[Los Angeles Chargers]]\n*[[Brent Rooker]], professional baseball player, [[Minnesota Twins]]\n*[[George Sherrill]],<ref name=\"ECS Legacy\" /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/baltimore-orioles-closer-george-sherrill-is-making-a-name-for-himself/article/45771|title=Baltimore Orioles closer George Sherrill is making a name for himself|date=27 July 2008|publisher=}}</ref> pitcher, [[Atlanta Braves]], [[Los Angeles Dodgers]]\n*[[Skal Labissi\u00e8re]], professional basketball player, [[Portland Trail Blazers]]\n*[[Christopher Daniel Duntsch]],<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.dmagazine.com/publications/d-magazine/2016/november/christopher-duntsch-dr-death/|title=Dr. Death: The Shocking Story of a Madman with a Scalpel}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/272320662/Christopher-Duntsch-Indictments| title=Christopher Duntsch Indictments}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.commercialappeal.com/story/news/2018/10/24/dr-death-podcast-christopher-duntsch-memphis-ut-health-science-center/1739766002/|title=Disgraced surgeon in 'Dr. Death' podcast grew up in Memphis, trained at UT Health Science Center}}</ref> AKA \"Dr. Death\", former neurosurgeon, serving life sentence for gross malpractice resulting in the death and maiming of multiple patients.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://ecseagles.com/ Evangelical Christian School]\n\n[[Category:Christian schools in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Nondenominational Christian schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Schools in Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Segregation academies in Tennessee]]\n", "name_user": "Awnearn", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I edited the reason that ECS was established. It was not because of desegregation, as that didn't begin until 1973, and ECS was established in 1965. (citation: Memphis City Schools Wikipedia p